<title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-systems-recognize-linear">
	<title>Recognizing linear equations</title>

	<statement><p>
		Which of the following is a <term><xref ref="definition-systems-linear-eqn" text="title" /></term>?
		<ol cols="2">
			<li xml:id="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-yes"><m> 2 a + 3 b - 6 c = 5 </m></li>
			<li xml:id="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-square"><m> 2 a^2 + 3 b - 6 c = 5 </m></li>
			<li xml:id="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-rearrange-then-yes"><m> 2 a = 5 - 3 b + 6 c </m></li>
			<li xml:id="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-parameter"><m> w + 2 x + 3 t y + 4 z = 0 </m></li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>

	<answer><p>
		Equations <xref ref="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-yes" text="local" /> and <xref ref="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-rearrange-then-yes" text="local" /> are linear,
		though we would typically rearrange the equation in <xref ref="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-rearrange-then-yes" text="local" /> so that all unknowns appear on the left-hand side.
		Equation <xref ref="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-square" text="local" /> is not linear because of the degree-<m>2</m> term <m>2 a^2</m>.
		Whether equation <xref ref="exercise-systems-recognize-linear-parameter" text="local" /> is considered linear or not depends on our perspective:
		we would probably consider <m>w</m>, <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m> to be unknowns,
		but what is the status of <m>t</m>?
		If the role of <m>t</m> is also to be an unknown,
		then the equation is not linear because of the degree-<m>2</m> term <m>3 t y</m>.
		But if the role of <m>t</m> is as an unspecified constant value,
		then the equation is linear in the other four variables.
	</p></answer>

</exercise>

<exercise>
	<title>Testing equation solutions</title>

	<introduction><p>
		For each collection of variable values,
		determine whether it constitutes a
		<term><xref ref="definition-systems-solution" text="custom">solution</xref></term>
		of the linear equation
		<me>-4 x + y + 9 z = 3</me>.
	</p></introduction>

	<task>
		<statement><p><m>x = 2, y = 2, z = 1</m>.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			Substitute the variable values into the left-hand side of the equation and compute
			<md>
				<mrow> \textrm{LHS} \amp = -4 x + y + 9 z </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -4 \cdot 2 + 2 + 9 \cdot 1 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -8 + 2 + 9 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 3 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \textrm{RHS} </mrow>
			</md>.
			As this collection of variable values satisfy the equation,
			it does constitute a solution of the equation.
		</p></solution>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement><p><m>x = 1, y = -2, z = 2</m>.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			Substitute the variable values into the left-hand side of the equation and compute
			<md>
				<mrow> \textrm{LHS} \amp = -4 x + y + 9 z </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -4 \cdot 1 + (-2) + 9 \cdot 2 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -4 - 2 + 18 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 12 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp \neq \textrm{RHS} </mrow>
			</md>.
			As this collection of variable values does not satisfy the equation,
			it does not constitute a solution of the equation.
		</p></solution>
	</task>

</exercise>

<exercise>
	<title>Testing system solutions</title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
		For each collection of variable values,
		determine whether it constitutes a
		<term><xref ref="definition-systems-solution" text="custom">solution</xref></term>
		of the system of linear equations
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcrcr}
				-4 x \amp + \amp   y \amp + \amp 9 z \amp = \amp  3, \\
				 3 x \amp - \amp 4 y \amp - \amp 4 z \amp = \amp -6, \\
				   x \amp - \amp   y \amp + \amp 2 z \amp = \amp 2
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>
		</p>
		<aside><title>Note</title><p>
			It is not necessary to <em>solve</em> the system of equations in order to <em>test</em> potential solutions.
		</p></aside>
	</introduction>

	<task>
		<statement><p><m>x = 2, y = 2, z = 1</m>.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			Substitute the variable values into each of the left-hand side of the equations and compute
			<md>
				<mrow> \textrm{LHS}_1 \amp = -4 x + y + 9 z </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -4 \cdot 2 + 2 + 9 \cdot 1 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -8 + 2 + 9 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 3 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \textrm{RHS}_1 </mrow>
			</md>,
			<md>
				<mrow> \textrm{LHS}_2 \amp = 3 x - 4 y - 4 z </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 3 \cdot 2 - 4 \cdot 2 - 4 \cdot 1 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 6 - 8 - 4 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -6 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \textrm{RHS}_2 </mrow>
			</md>,
			<md>
				<mrow> \textrm{LHS}_3 \amp = x - y + 2 z </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 2 - 2 + 2 \cdot 1 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 0 + 2 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 2 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \textrm{RHS}_3 </mrow>
			</md>.
			As this collection of variable values simultaneously satisfies all equations in the system,
			it does constitute a solution of the system.
		</p></solution>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement><p><m>x = -2, y = 4, z = -1</m>.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			Substitute the variable values into each of the left-hand side of the equations and compute
			<md>
				<mrow> \textrm{LHS}_1 \amp = -4 x + y + 9 z </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -4 \cdot (-2) + 4 + 9 \cdot (-1) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 8 + 4 - 9 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 3 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \textrm{RHS}_1 </mrow>
			</md>,
			<md>
				<mrow> \textrm{LHS}_2 \amp = 3 x - 4 y - 4 z </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 3 \cdot (-2) - 4 \cdot 4 - 4 \cdot (-1) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -6 - 16 + 4 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = -18 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp \neq \textrm{RHS}_2 </mrow>
			</md>.
			There is no need to continue on to the third equation,
			as we may already conclude that this collection of variable values does not simultaneously satisfy all equations in the system.
			Therefore, it does not constitute a solution of the system.
		</p></solution>
	</task>

</exercise>

